3.\n|-\n| width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" valign=\"top\" | Von allen gem\u00e4\u00df Abs. 1 oder Abs. 2 dieses Artikels getroffenen Ma\u00dfnahmen hat der Reichspr\u00e4sident unverz\u00fcglich dem Reichstag Kenntnis zu geben. Die Ma\u00dfnahmen sind auf Verlangen des Reichstags au\u00dfer Kraft zu setzen.\n| width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#ffdead;\" valign=\"top\" | The President of the Reich must inform the Reichstag without delay of all measures taken in accordance with Paragraphs 1 or 2 of this Article.  These measures are to be revoked on the demand of the Reichstag.\n|-\n| width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" valign=\"top\" | Bei Gefahr im Verzuge kann die Landesregierung f\u00fcr ihr Gebiet einstweilige Ma\u00dfnahmen der in Abs. 2 bezeichneten Art treffen. Die Ma\u00dfnahmen sind auf Verlangen des Reichspr\u00e4sidenten oder des Reichstags au\u00dfer Kraft zu setzen.\n| width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#ffdead;\" valign=\"top\" | If danger is imminent, a State government may, for its own territory, take temporary measures as provided in Paragraph 2. These measures are to be revoked on the demand of the President of the Reich or of the Reichstag.\n|-\n| width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" valign=\"top\" | Das N\u00e4here bestimmt ein Reichsgesetz.\n| width=\"50%\" style=\"background:#ffdead;\" valign=\"top\" | Details are to be determined by a law of the Reich.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Machtergreifung]]\n* [[State of emergency]]\n* [[State of exception]] \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<!-- ==External links==\n* dead link [http://web.jjay.cuny.edu/~jobrien/reference/ob13.html Selected articles of Weimar constitution] -->\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1919 in law]]\n[[Category:Emergency laws]]\n[[Category:Legal history of Germany]]\n[[Category:1933 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Weimar Republic]]\n", "name_user": "Martin Urbanec", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Article_48_(Weimar_Constitution)"}
{"title_page": "Rao Bahadur", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}My Grand Father Kashinath Krushnaji Kalkar was also the one Rao Bahadur in British Raj who then became Dy Collector \n{{short description|Honour bestowed during British rule in India}}\n[[File:Rao Bahadur Medal.jpg|thumb|Rao Bahadur Medal]]\n'''Rai Bahadur''' (also '''Rao Bahadur''' in [[South India]]), abbreviated '''R.B.''', was a [[title of honour]] bestowed during [[British Raj|British rule]] in India to individuals for their service to the Empire. The title was accompanied by a medal called a Title Badge. Translated, ''Rao'' means \"prince\", and ''[[Baghatur|Bahadur]]'' means \"brave\" or \"most honourable\". The equivalent title for [[Muslim]] and [[Parsi]] subjects was ''[[Khan Bahadur]]''. For [[Sikh]]s it was ''Sardar Bahadur''.\n\nThose awarded the [[Rai Sahib]] title were usually elevated to the next rank, that of Rao Bahadur, which was in turn below the rank of [[Dewan Bahadur]].<ref name=j>{{Cite web |last=Jalan |first=Aditya |date=2009 |title=Dewan Bahadur 1944\u20131954 |url=http://www.quilahouse.com/dewan-bahadur.htm |publisher=Quila House and the Jalan Collection: A Brief Introduction |access-date=29 July 2018}}</ref> These titles were subordinate to the two orders of knighthood, being: the lesser [[Order of the Indian Empire]] and the higher [[Order of the Star of India]]. A holder of a Rai Sahib, Rai Bahadur or Diwan Bahadur title came lower in the order of precedence.\n\n==Some people awarded the Rao Bahadur title==\n* Rao Bahadur Sadashiva Jairam Dehadrai, Freedom fighter, philanthropist, sanskrit scholar and vedic philosopher. Professor of Sanskrit, Jabalpur College. Conferred title of Rao Bahadur on 1st January 1910, in recognition of his learning and public services.<ref name=\"Who's Who in India, 1911 Coronation Edition, p 27\"> [https://ia801605.us.archive.org/6/items/in.ernet.dli.2015.209992/2015.209992.Whos-Who_text.pdf Who's Who 1911 Coronation Edition], Lucknow,  Newul Kishore Press, 1911 (page 27)</ref>     \n* Rao Bahadur Sir [[Kurma Venkata Reddy Naidu]], Chief Minister of Madras Presidency.\n*Rai Bahadur Satyen Nath (S.N.) Mukherjee, First Indian origin Deputy Commissioner of Indian Police, Calcutta. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Channa|first=Subhadra Mitra|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=Qak0AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA79&dq=Rai+Bahadur+S.N.+Mukherjee&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTh_CcoLvoAhUb8HMBHTshAuUQ6AEIKzAB#v=onepage&q=Rai%20Bahadur%20S.N.%20Mukherjee&f=false|title=Gender in South Asia|last2=Channa|first2=Subhadra|date=2013-09-05|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-04361-9|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Gupta (IAS.)|first=G. S.|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=76ZIAAAAYAAJ&dq=Rai+Bahadur+S.N.+Mukherjee&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=S.N.+Mukherjee|title=Free Masonry in India|date=1991|publisher=G.S. Gupta|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Court|first=India Supreme|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=a4M2AAAAIAAJ&dq=Rai+Bahadur+S.N.+Mukherjee&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Deputy+commissioner+S.N.+Mukherjee|title=Indian Factories & Labour Reports|date=1963|publisher=Law Publishing House.|language=en}}</ref>\n* Rao Bahadur [[A. Veeriya Vandayar]], philanthropist.\n* Rao Bahadur [[P. I. Chinnaswamy Pillai]], First Municipal Chairman - Palakkad.\n* Rao Bahadur [[C. Jambulingam Mudaliar]], Indian politician and freedom-fighter.\n* Rao Bahadur [[Ranchhodlal Chhotalal]], textile mill pioneer and philanthropist\n* Rao Bahadur Dharmapravartha [[Gubbi Thotadappa]] , Dharmachathra Founder, [[Karnataka]].\n* [[Chhotu Ram|Rao Bahadur Sir Chhotu Ram]], Minister for Agriculture and Home Affairs, erstwhile Punjab, 1945.\n* Rao Bahadur Dr. Ram Dhan Singh, pioneer agricultural scientist, Principal, College of Agriculture Lyallpur, Erstwhile Punjab, 1947.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.drramdhansingh.org/biography|title = Biography of Ch. Ram Dhan Singh|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> \n* Rao Bahadur [[P. K. Monnappa]], South Indian Police Chief of three states, Madras, Hyderabad and Mysore.\n* Rai Bahadur Sir [[Kailash Chandra Bose]],CIE,OBE,first Knighted Indian Physician.<ref>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5197519/]</ref>\n\n* [[Rai Saligram|Rai Bahadur Saligram]], Pipal Mandi, [[Agra]]\n* Rai Bahadur [[Seth Vishandas Nihalchand]], [[Sindhi Hindus|Sindhi]] politician, social reformer, philanthropist\n* Rai Bahadur Jagan Nath Bhandari [[Raj Ratan]], [[Dewan]] of [[Idar (princely state)|Idar State]]<ref>[http://books.google.co.in/books?ei=2ZwiTrrqCcqqrAf9u-yaAg&ct=result&id=xacSAAAAIAAJ&dq=Dewan+of+Idar+State&q=Dewan++Idar#search_anchor Bhandari Jagan Nath Rai Bhadur, Raj Ratan, Dewan of Idar State], The Times of India directory and year book including who's who, Volume 32, 1945</ref>\n* Rai Bahadur [[Chaudhary Dewan Chand Saini]], [[MBE]], [[Gurdaspur]], [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]]\n* Rai Bahadur [[Ranadaprasad Saha]], philanthropist\n* [[Rai Bahadur Jagmal Raja Chauhan]], industrialist and noted railway contractor\n* [[Rai Bahadur Jairam Valji Chauhan]], industrialist\n* [[Rai Bahadur Gujar Mal Modi]], Founder of the Modi Group\n* [[Mohan Singh Oberoi|Rai Bahadur Mohan Singh Oberoi]], founder of [[Oberoi Group]] \n* [[Rai Bahadur Bakshi Badri Nath Chhibber]]\n* [[Rai Bahadur Tirath Singh Bakshi]]\n* [[Rai Bahadur Amba Prasad]], philanthropist of Delhi\n* Rai Bahadur Dharmarathnakara [[Arcot Narrainsawmy Mudaliar]], philanthropist.\n* Rai Bahadur [[Purna Chandra Lahiri]], Indian Police Officer, [[Calcutta]]\n* Rai Bahadur [[S. A. Saminatha Iyer]], Indian independence activist.\n* Sardar Bahadur [[Jagat Singh (Sant)]], [[Faisalabad|Lyallpur]], pre-partition [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]\n* Rai Bahadur [[Upendranath Brahmachari]], [[Calcutta|Bengal Presidency]], Discovery of urea stibamine for the treatment of [[Kala Azar]]\n\n\n*Rajendranath Dutt, judge, Bengal<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\">[https://archive.org/details/indianbiographic00raoc/page/26 The Indian biographical dictionary], by C. Hayavando Rao, 1915 (page 26)</ref>\n*Babu Ram Sadan Bhattacharji, deputy magistrate, Bengal<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Babu Bahadur Singh, honorary magistrate, Pilibhit<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Sahu Parsotam Saran Kothiwala, member of the district board, Moradabad<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Soti Raghubans Lal, subordinate judge, Shahjehanpur<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Sadh Achraj Lal, honorary magistrate and member of the municipal board, Mirzapur<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Babu Shuhrat Singh, Zemindar of Chandpur and honorary magistrate, Basti<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Balkishen Kaul, surgeon, lecturer, and superintendent of Lahore Medical college<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Priya Nath Dutt, assistant registrar, Punjab University<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Lada Damodar Das, extrajudicial assistant commissioner in the Punjab<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Lala Jai Lal, member of the Municipal Committee, Simla<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Jwala Prasad, government pleader<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Babu Nalini Kanta Ray, Dastidar of Assam<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Betharam Sarma, sub-deputy collector, Tezpur, Assam<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 26\"/>\n*Dewan Jaggatnath, secretary to the municipal committee and district board, Dera Ismail Khan<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 27\">[https://archive.org/details/indianbiographic00raoc/page/27 The Indian biographical dictionary], by C. Hayavando Rao, 1915 (page 27)</ref>\n* Seth Sarupchand Hukamchand, merchant, Indore<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 27\"/>\n*Manik Lal Joshi, chief minister of Bundi, Rajputana<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 27\"/>\n*Akshey Kumar Sarkar, superintendent, Department of Commerce and Industry, Government of India<ref name=\"Hayavando, p 27\"/>\n\n<!-- HI! YOU'RE SEEING THIS MESSAGE BECAUSE YOU TRIED TO ADD A NEW ENTRY TO THE LIST! NEW ENTRIES ARE WELCOME ON THE LIST ****ONLY IF**** YOU HAVE SUPPLIED A RE